# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 40-s-w
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:40-s-w/22-remington-jet] The **.22 Remington Jet** (**5.6x33mmR**) is a .22 in (5.6mm) American centerfire revolver and rifle cartridge.
[src:40-s-w/22-remington-jet] Developed jointly by Remington and Smith & Wesson, it was to be used in the Model 53 revolver, which first appeared late in 1961.
[src:40-s-w/22-remington-jet] While it traced its origins to potent wildcats such as the .224 Harvey Kay-Chuk, which ultimately derive from the .22 Hornet, it was a bottlenecked cartridge based upon the .357 Magnum case necked down to a .22 caliber bullet, with an unusually long tapered shoulder.
[src:40-s-w/22-remington-jet] By 1972, the Model 53 remained the only revolver chambered for it, while Marlin in 1972 was planning a lever rifle in .22 Jet.
[src:40-s-w/22-remington-jet] The .22 Jet was also a factory chambering for the Thompson/Center Contender and the design allowed for it to reach its full potential, having no cylinder gap and no case setback.
[src:40-s-w/22-remington-jet] The .22 Jet was designed as a flat-shooting hunting round for handguns, and it is suitable for handgun hunting of varmints and medium game out to 100 yd (90 m).
[src:40-s-w/22-remington-jet] The 2460 ft/s (750 m/s) and 535 ft-lbf (725 J) claimed for factory test loads did not prove out in service weapons.
[src:40-s-w/22-short] Developed for self defense, the modern .22 short, though still used in a few pocket pistols and mini-revolvers, is mainly used as a quiet round for practice by the recreational shooter.
[src:40-s-w/22-short] The .22 short was popularly used in shooting galleries at fairs and arcades; several rifle makers produced "gallery" models for .22 short exclusively.
[src:40-s-w/22-short] Due to its low recoil and good inherent accuracy, the .22 short was used for the Olympic 25 meter rapid fire pistol event until 2004, and it was allowed in the shooting part of modern pentathlon competitions before they switched to air pistols.
[src:40-s-w/22-short] Several makes of starter pistols use .22 short blank cartridges.
[src:40-s-w/22-short] Some powder-actuated nail guns use .22 short blanks as a power source.
[src:40-s-w/22-short] Most .22 short bullets are made of lead (usually coated with grease or wax, or copper) in round nose or hollow point styles.
[src:40-s-w/22-short] Bullets for use at shooting galleries were often made of compressed powdered metal that disintegrated on impact to avoid ricochets and over-penetration of backstops.
[src:40-s-w/22-short] The standard velocity .22 short launches a 29-grain (1.9 g) bullet at 1,045 feet per second (319 m/s) with 70 ft·lbf (95 J) of energy from a 22 in (559 mm) rifle barrel and can penetrate 2 inches (51 mm) of soft pine.
[src:40-s-w/22-short] As a hunting round, the high velocity hollow point Short is useful only for small game such as tree squirrels and rabbits.
[src:40-s-w/22-short] For small game hunting in general, the greater energy and wider ammunition selection of the .22 long rifle make it a more popular choice.
[src:40-s-w/22-short] In the American South, the .22 short hollow point is still very popular for use on raccoons, which are treed at night using dogs and shooting is at close range.
[src:40-s-w/22-short] In some states, the .22 short is the only legal round to use for such hunting.
[src:40-s-w/22-short] Although the .22 long rifle has surpassed the .22 short in the marketplace, many ammunition companies still produce .22 shorts, and in a fairly wide variety.
[src:40-s-w/22-short] Most makers utilize the standard 29-grain (1.9 g) solid round nose bullet and 27-grain (1.7 g) hollow point bullet weights for the .22 short.
[src:40-s-w/22-short] Several types are made by CCI: a CB Short at 727 ft/s (222 m/s), target Shorts at 830 ft/s (250 m/s), their standard Short round with plated round nose bullet at 1,080 ft/s (330 m/s), and a high speed hunting load with plated hollow point bullet at 1,105 ft/s (337 m/s).
[src:40-s-w/22-short] The .22 short high-velocity exceeds the performance of the .22 long (with the exception of CCI's High Velocity 1217fps long loading), and the .22 short has displaced the .22 long as an alternate to the .22 long rifle for many .22 shooters.
[src:40-s-w/22-short] Fiocchi makes their Exacta Compensated Super Match SM200 with lead round nose at 650 ft/s (200 m/s).
[src:40-s-w/22-short] Remington produces a high velocity plated round nose at 1,095 ft/s (334 m/s).
[src:40-s-w/22-short] Aguila makes both a match lead round nose at 1,095 ft/s (334 m/s), and a "high speed" round with plated bullet also listed at 1,095 ft/s (334 m/s).
[src:40-s-w/22-short] Also available is the RWS R25 match ammunition at 560 ft/s (170 m/s).
[src:40-s-w/22-short] Eley also makes their rapid fire match cartridge at 750 ft/s (230 m/s).
[src:40-s-w/22-short] Most of the target oriented and CB Shorts are very quiet, due to being subsonic.
[src:40-s-w/22-short] When fired from a full-length rifle barrel, most .22 short loadings are as quiet as if not quieter than, the average air rifle.
[src:40-s-w/22-short] There have been many rifles chambered for the .22 short over the years, but only several lever action rifles are currently chambered for this round, notably Henry Repeating Arms and Marlin Firearms Co. lever action rifles.
[src:40-s-w/22-short] The Marlin Golden 39A model represents the oldest and longest continuously produced shoulder firearm in the world.
[src:40-s-w/22-short] Many rifles in .22 short were made between 1901 and 1940, mostly intended for gallery shooting and small game hunting.
[src:40-s-w/22-short] Remington and Winchester produced the most rifles in .22 short.
[src:40-s-w/22-short] Remington has made their Model 24 and Model 241 "Speedmaster" semi-autos as well as their Model 12 and 121 "Fieldmaster" pump actions in .22 short.
[src:40-s-w/22-short] Remington's Nylon 66 GS Gallery Special (1962 to 1981) was one of the last .22 short-only rifles made especially for shooting gallery use.
[src:40-s-w/22-short] Winchester produced a variety of different rifles in .22 short, including the 1873 lever action, 1885 single shot (in both low wall and high wall variations), Model 1890, 1906 and 62A pump actions, Model 74 semi-auto, and Model 61 pump action.
[src:40-s-w/22-short] Many of their bolt-action rifles were available on a special-order basis in .22 short.
[src:40-s-w/22-short] Browning/FN also produced their takedown semi-auto in .22 short, on the same John Browning design upon which the Remington Model 24 is based.
[src:40-s-w/22-short] Many of these rifles are now collector's items, particularly the Winchesters, and demand a premium in price over the same rifle chambered in .22 long rifle.
[src:40-s-w/22-short] Many rifles marked ".22 short, long and long rifle" (or ".22 S, L, LR") will not shoot shorts with the same accuracy as they will a long rifle round nor as accurately as a rifle designed for .22 short.
[src:40-s-w/22-short] This is due to the excess chamber length needed to allow chambering of .22 LR cartridges.
[src:40-s-w/22-short] This requires the bullet from a .22 short to travel a short distance before it engages the rifling, which is detrimental to accuracy.
[src:40-s-w/22-short] In addition, barrels made for .22 short are rifled with a rate of twist of one turn in twenty inches, while barrels made for .22 long rifle have a twist of one turn in sixteen inches.
[src:40-s-w/220-rook] The **.220 Rook / 5.7x18mmR**, also known as the **.220 Long Centrefire**, is an obsolete British centerfire rifle cartridge.
[src:40-s-w/220-rook] The .220 Rook is a rimmed cartridge originally designed for use in rook rifles.
[src:40-s-w/220-rook] It was designed and produced in Britain in the 1880s.
[src:40-s-w/220-rook] It is believed to be an early centrefire version of the .22 Long Rifle rimfire cartridge.
[src:40-s-w/220-rook] The .220 Rook fired a bullet of 30 grains (1.9 g) weight driven by 5 grains (0.32 g) of black powder, it was designed for hunting small game and target shooting, although many considered it too small for practical hunting purposes.
[src:40-s-w/221-remington-fireball] The **.221 Remington Fireball** (5.7×35mm), often simply referred to as **.221 Fireball**, is a centerfire cartridge developed by Remington Arms Company in 1963 as a special round for use in their experimental single-shot bolt-action pistol, the XP-100.
[src:40-s-w/221-remington-fireball] It is a shortened version of the .222 Remington and is popular for varmint and small predator hunting, as well as among target shooters.
[src:40-s-w/221-remington-fireball] The .221 Fireball is used in both pistols & rifles.
[src:40-s-w/221-remington-fireball] In the early 1960s Remington was working on an experimental bolt-action pistol based on their Model 600 action.
[src:40-s-w/221-remington-fireball] The goal was a highly accurate pistol that would be well suited for competition.
[src:40-s-w/221-remington-fireball] After working with the .222 Remington they determined that it contained more powder capacity than was necessary to work efficiently in the shorter barrels of pistols.
[src:40-s-w/221-remington-fireball] While rifle barrels commonly range in length from 14.5 to 26 in (37 to 66 cm), pistol barrels are typically much shorter, ranging from 2 to 12 in (5.1 to 30.5 cm) although occasionally up to 16 in (41 cm) for some competition barrels.
[src:40-s-w/221-remington-fireball] As a result, Remington decided to develop a shorter version of the .222 Remington cartridge, optimized for use in the XP-100.
[src:40-s-w/221-remington-fireball] While production of XP-100 pistols chambered in .221 Fireball was eventually canceled after 1985, Thompson Center Arms produced various single-shot pistols chambered for the .221 Fireball as part of their Contender and Encore models.
[src:40-s-w/221-remington-fireball] Rifles chambered for the .221 Fireball include the Remington 700 and the Ceska zbrojovka CZ 527.
[src:40-s-w/221-remington-fireball] Despite its smaller size, the .221 Fireball is capable of velocities nearly equal to that of the .222 Remington largely due to its higher SAAMI pressure.
[src:40-s-w/221-remington-fireball] The maximum SAAMI pressure level for the .221 Fireball is 52,000 C.U.P. as compared to 46,000 C.U.P. for the .222 Remington.
[src:40-s-w/221-remington-fireball] The purpose of the increased pressure was to allow it to perform more effectively in the shorter barrel of the XP-100.
[src:40-s-w/221-remington-fireball] The .221 Fireball produces the highest velocity of any commercial pistol cartridge.
[src:40-s-w/221-remington-fireball] The .221 Fireball has been used by wildcatters to create a small efficient .17 caliber cartridge.
[src:40-s-w/221-remington-fireball] The most common is the .17 Mach IV which is essentially the .221 necked down to the smaller caliber.
[src:40-s-w/221-remington-fireball] This cartridge is reported to have a very flat trajectory and to be relatively quiet with low recoil.
[src:40-s-w/221-remington-fireball] It has been so popular as a wildcat that in 2007 Remington legitimized it by introducing their version only slightly different from the Mach IV and calling it the .17 Remington Fireball.
[src:40-s-w/221-remington-fireball] A .20 caliber version is also gaining popularity called the .20 VarTarg (VT), "vartarg" being the combination of the words "**var**mint" and "**targ**et".
[src:40-s-w/221-remington-fireball] The .221 Fireball has also been used as the base for the .300 Whisper, sometimes referred to as the .300/.221 or .300 Fireball.
[src:40-s-w/221-remington-fireball] It is also the basis for other cartridges in J.D.
[src:40-s-w/221-remington-fireball] Jones' Whisper family including the 6 mm Whisper, which has been adopted by Knight's Armament Corporation for their Knight's Armament Company PDW as the 6×35mm PDW.
[src:40-s-w/224-boz] The **.224 Boz** cartridge was developed in the late 1990s, designed as a candidate replacement cartridge for adoption as the standardized NATO ("STANAG") Personal defense weapon PDW round, originally solicited to replace the longstanding NATO standard (STANAG) 9×19mm Parabellum.
[src:40-s-w/224-boz] It was going to be the British entry, to be evaluated alongside the Belgian FN 5.7×28mm and the German HK 4.6×30mm armor-piercing cartridges.
[src:40-s-w/224-boz] The solicitation would also seek to find, test and standardize a PDW cartridge capable of, at the minimum, defeating the Collaborative Research Into Small Arms Technology (CRISAT) body armour of the time.
[src:40-s-w/224-boz] The .224 Boz began as a 10mm Auto case necked down to .223 in (5.7 mm).
[src:40-s-w/224-boz] Original trials were successful, with this round firing a 50 gr (3.2 g) projectile chronographed at over 2,500 ft/s (760 m/s).
[src:40-s-w/224-boz] During development a version based upon the 9×19 Parabellum case was also evaluated, which carried the significant advantage of being able to be utilized in pre-existing NATO standard 9×19 Parabellum caliber firearms by means of a relatively cheap barrel and caliber swap.
[src:40-s-w/224-boz] The .22 TCM takes advantage of this same concept in its sub-variant, the .22 TCM 9R.
[src:40-s-w/25-remington] The **.25 Remington** (also known as the .25 Remington Auto-Loading) is an American rifle cartridge.
[src:40-s-w/25-remington] A rimless, smokeless powder design, this cartridge was considered to be very accurate by period firearm experts and suitable for game up to deer and black bear.
[src:40-s-w/25-remington] It was based on the .30 Remington cartridge.
[src:40-s-w/25-remington] The .25 Remington cartridge dates to 1906 and its introduction by Remington in the Model 8 rifle.
[src:40-s-w/25-remington] Other rifles chambered for the .25 Remington include the Remington 14 slide-action, Remington 30 bolt action, Stevens 425 lever-action, and Standard Arms rifles.
[src:40-s-w/25-remington] Due to their similar dimensions, the .25 Remington, .30 Remington, and .32 Remington together were known as the Remington Rimless cartridge series.
[src:40-s-w/25-remington] Firearm manufacturers generally offered all three of these cartridges as chamberings in a rifle model rather than just one of the series.
[src:40-s-w/25-remington] The series was competitive with Winchester Repeating Arms Company's contemporary lever action offerings: .25-35 Winchester, .30-30, and .32 Winchester Special.
[src:40-s-w/25-remington] The .25 Remington case was shortened and necked down to .22 caliber to form Lysle Kilbourn's wildcat .22 Kilbourn Magnum Junior and the rimless version of Leslie Lindahl's wildcat .22 Chucker.
[src:40-s-w/297-250-rook] The **.297/250 Rook / 6.4x21mmR** is an obsolete centerfire rifle cartridge developed by Holland & Holland.
[src:40-s-w/297-250-rook] The .297/250 Rook is a bottlenecked rimmed cartridge originally designed for use in rook rifles for hunting small game and target shooting.
[src:40-s-w/297-250-rook] This cartridge was introduced by Holland & Holland some time before 1880 by blowing out the neck of the .297/230 Morris Long to .250 in (6.4 mm).
[src:40-s-w/297-250-rook] This cartridge is a contemporary of the .255 Jeffery Rook and upon their release the pair competed heavily with the very popular .300 Rook.
[src:40-s-w/297-250-rook] As with other rook rifle cartridges, the .297/250 Rook was superseded by the .22 Long Rifle.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] The **.40 S&W** is a rimless pistol cartridge developed jointly by American firearms manufacturers Smith & Wesson and Winchester in 1990.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] The .40 S&W was developed as a law enforcement cartridge designed to duplicate the performance of the Federal Bureau of Investigation's (FBI) reduced-velocity 10mm Auto cartridge which could be retrofitted into medium-frame (9 mm size) semi-automatic handguns.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] It uses 0.40-inch-diameter (10 mm) bullets typically ranging in weight from 105 to 200 grains (6.8 to 13.0 g).
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] In the aftermath of the 1986 FBI Miami shootout, in which two FBI special agents were killed and five wounded, the FBI started the process of testing 9×19mm Parabellum and .45 ACP ammunition in preparation to replace its standard-issue revolver with a semi-automatic pistol.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] The semi-automatic pistol offered two advantages over the revolver: increased ammunition capacity and increased ease of reloading during a gunfight.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] The FBI was satisfied with the performance of its .38 Special +P 158 gr (10.2 g) lead semi-wadcutter hollowpoint (LSWCHP) cartridge ("FBI load") based on decades of dependable performance.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] Ammunition for the new semi-automatic pistol had to deliver terminal performance equal or superior to the .38 Special FBI load.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] The FBI developed a series of practically oriented tests involving eight test events that they believed reasonably represented the kinds of situations that FBI agents commonly encountered in shooting incidents.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] During tests of the 9×19mm and .45 ACP ammunition, the unit chief of the FBI Firearms Training Unit, John Hall, decided to include tests of the 10mm Auto cartridge, supplying his own Colt Delta Elite 10mm semi-automatic, and personally hand-loaded ammunition.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] The FBI's tests revealed that a 170–180 gr (11.0–11.7 g) JHP 10mm bullet, propelled between 900–1,000 ft/s (270–300 m/s), achieved desired terminal performance without the heavy recoil associated with conventional 10mm ammunition (1,300–1,400 ft/s (400–430 m/s)).
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] The FBI contacted Smith & Wesson and requested that it design a handgun to FBI specifications, based on the existing large-frame Smith & Wesson Model 4506 .45 ACP handgun, that would reliably function with the FBI's reduced-velocity 10mm ammunition.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] During this collaboration with the FBI, S&W realized that downsizing the 10mm full-power to meet the FBI's medium-velocity specification meant less powder and more airspace in the case.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] They found that by removing the airspace they could shorten the 10mm case enough to fit within their medium-frame 9mm handguns and load it with a 180 gr (11.7 g) JHP bullet to produce ballistic performance identical to the FBI's reduced-velocity 10mm cartridge.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] S&W then teamed with Winchester to produce a new cartridge, the .40 S&W.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] It uses a small pistol primer whereas the 10mm cartridge uses a large pistol primer.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] The .40 S&W cartridge debuted January 17, 1990, along with the new Smith & Wesson Model 4006 pistol, although it was several months before the pistols were available for purchase.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] Austrian manufacturer Glock Ges.m.b.H. were commercially available ahead of Smith & Wesson in 1990, with pistols chambered in .40 S&W (the Glock 22 and Glock 23) which were announced a week before the 4006.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] Glock's rapid introduction was aided by its engineering of a pistol chambered in 10mm Auto, the Glock 20, only a short time earlier.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] Since the .40 S&W uses the same bore diameter and case head as the 10mm Auto, it was merely a matter of adapting the 10mm design to the shorter 9×19mm Parabellum frames.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] The new guns and ammunition were an immediate success, and pistols in the new caliber were adopted by several law enforcement agencies around the nation, including the FBI, which adopted the Glock pistol in .40 S&W in May 1997.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] The popularity of the .40 S&W accelerated with the passage of the now-expired Federal Assault Weapons Ban of 1994, which prohibited sales of pistol or rifle magazines that could hold more than ten cartridges, regardless of caliber.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] Several U.S. states, and a number of local governments, also banned or regulated so-called "high-capacity" magazines.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] As a result, many new firearm buyers limited to purchasing pistols with a maximum magazine capacity of 10 rounds chose pistols in the .40 S&W chambering instead of smaller-diameter cartridges such as the 9×19mm (9mm Luger or 9mm Parabellum).
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] The .40 S&W case length and overall cartridge length are shortened, but other dimensions except for case web and wall thickness remain identical to the 10mm Auto.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] Both cartridges headspace on the mouth of the case.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] Thus in a semi-auto, they are not interchangeable.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] Fired from a 10mm semi-auto, the .40 Smith & Wesson cartridge will headspace on the extractor and the bullet will jump a 0.142 inches (3.6 mm) freebore just like a .38 Special fired from a .357 Magnum revolver.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] If the cartridge is not held by the extractor, the chances for a ruptured primer are great.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] Smith & Wesson does make a double-action revolver (the Model 610) that can fire either cartridge via use of moon clips.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] A single-action revolver in the .38–40 chambering can also fire .40 or 10mm rounds provided it is equipped with a correctly sized cylinder.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] Some .40 caliber handguns can be converted to 9mm with a special purpose-made barrel, magazine change, and other parts.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] In 2015, the FBI announced they were going back to 9mm ammunition, citing advancements in ballistic technology and increased accuracy in a gunfight.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] The FBI also found that .40 S&W rounds were causing excessive wear on pistols and were harder to control for some agents.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] This has caused a substantial contribution to the .40 S&W's decline in popularity with law enforcement in the US.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] The .40 S&W has a 1.25 ml (19.3 gr H2O) cartridge case capacity.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] The common rifling twist rate for this cartridge is 406 millimetres (16.0 in), with 6 grooves, land diameter 9.91 mm, groove diameter 10.17 mm, and land width 3.05 mm, and the primer type is small pistol.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] According to the official C.I.P. guidelines, the .40 S&W case can handle up to 225 MPa (32,600 psi) piezo pressure.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] In C.I.P.-regulated countries, every pistol/cartridge combo has to be proofed at 130% of this maximum C.I.P. pressure to certify for sale to consumers.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] The SAAMI pressure limit for the .40 S&W is set at 241.32 MPa (35,001 psi) piezo pressure.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] The .40 S&W cartridge has been popular with law enforcement agencies in the United States, Canada, Australia, and Brazil.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] While possessing nearly identical accuracy, drift and drop as the 9mm Parabellum, it has an energy advantage over the 9mm Parabellum and .45 ACP, and a more manageable recoil than the 10mm Auto cartridge.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] Marshall & Sanow (and other hydrostatic shock proponents) contend that with good jacketed hollow point bullets, the more energetic loads for the .40 S&W can also create hydrostatic shock in human-sized living targets.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] Based on the ideal terminal ballistic performance in ordnance gelatin during lab testing in the late 1980s and early 1990s, the .40 S&W earned status as "the ideal cartridge for personal defense and law enforcement".
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] Ballistically the .40 S&W is almost identical to the .38-40 Winchester introduced in 1874, as they share the same bullet diameter and bullet weight, and have similar muzzle velocities.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] The energy of the .40 S&W exceeds standard-pressure .45 ACP loadings, generating between 350 foot-pounds (470 J) and 500 foot-pounds (680 J) of energy, depending on bullet weight.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] Both the .40 S&W and the 9mm Parabellum operate at a 35,000 pounds per square inch (240 MPa) SAAMI maximum, compared to a 21,000 pounds per square inch (140 MPa) maximum for .45 ACP.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] .40 S&W pistols with standard (not extended) double-stack magazines can hold as many as 16 cartridges.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] While not displacing the 9mm Parabellum, the .40 S&W is commonly used in law enforcement applications in keeping with its origin with the FBI.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] Select U.S. special operations units have available the .40 S&W and .45 ACP for their pistols.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] The United States Coast Guard, having dual duties as maritime law enforcement and military deployments, has adopted the SIG Sauer P229R DAK in .40 S&W as their standard sidearm.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] However, as of 2020, the Coast Guard has adopted the Glock 19 GEN5 MOS as its new sidearm.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] Numerous federal and local law enforcement agencies are currently in the process of transitioning from .40 S&W to 9mm, most notably the FBI, who adopted 9mm firearms in 2015.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] Customs and Border Protection adopted 9mm Glock handguns, replacing the .40 S&W Heckler & Koch P2000 CBP was previously using.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] The .40 S&W was originally loaded at subsonic velocity (984.25 ft/s (300.00 m/s)) with a 180 grains (11.7 g) bullet.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] Since its introduction, various loads have been created, with the majority being either 155, 165 or 180 gr (10.0, 10.7 or 11.7 g).
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] However, there are some bullets with weights as light as 135 gr (8.7 g) and as heavy as 200 gr (13.0 g).
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] Cor-Bon and Winchester both offer a 135 gr (8.7 g) JHP and Cor-Bon also offers a 140 gr (9.1 g) Barnes XPB hollow-point.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] The .40 S&W has been noted in a number of cartridge case failures involving older Glock pistols, due to the relatively large area of unsupported case head in those barrels, given its allowed chamber pressure level.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] The feed ramp on the Glock .40 S&W pistols is larger than on other Glocks, which leaves the rear bottom of the case unsupported, and it is in this unsupported area that the cases fail.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] Most, but not all, of the failures have occurred with reloaded or remanufactured ammunition.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] Cartridges loaded at or above the SAAMI pressure, or slightly oversized cases which fire slightly out of battery are often considered to be the cause of these failures, which are commonly referred to as "kaBooms" or "kB!" for short.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] While these case failures do not often injure the person holding the pistol, the venting of high-pressure gas tends to eject the magazine out of the magazine well in a spectacular fashion, and usually destroys the pistol.
[src:40-s-w/40-s-w] In some cases, the barrel will also fail, blowing the top of the chamber off.
